If we express these modalities as a matrix of intersections between normative, operative, and evaluative levels (deontic dimension) and data, information, knowledge, and wisdom (epistemic dimension), we create a rich 12-cell framework:
Data	Information	Knowledge	Wisdom
Normative	Data ethics standards	Information disclosure requirements	Epistemic duties	Prudential ideals
Operative	Data handling practices	Information processing actions	Knowledge application	Wise decision execution
Evaluative	Data quality assessment	Information value judgments	Knowledge validation	Wisdom effectiveness criteria
Each intersection produces a distinct semantic category. For example:
Normative × Knowledge: Professional knowledge standards, epistemic responsibilities
Operative × Information: Communication protocols, information sharing behaviors
Evaluative × Wisdom: Judgment quality metrics, practical wisdom assessment
This framework yields what could be called a "normative-epistemic matrix" - a structured taxonomy for understanding how obligation and knowledge interact across different levels of complexity and implementation. This matrix is particularly valuable in fields like information ethics, professional regulation, and organizational knowledge management.

